[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(39) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "All the widows stood by him weeping.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—We have apparently the same organisation of charity as that which prevailed in the Church at Jerusalem. The “widows” of the Church were the object of a special provision. (See Note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 6:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) The “coats,” were the close-fitting tunics worn next the body, the “garments” the looser outer cloaks that were worn over them. (See Note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 5:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) These were now exhibited by those who were mourning over the loss of their benefactress. It is probable that the garments were for the use of men and boys, as well as women, and that the “widows” had been fellow-workers with her in making them. She was, as it were, at the head of a Sisterhood of Mercy.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Which Dorcas made.—More accurately, used to make.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Which Dorcas made.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—More accurately, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "used to make.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Acts 9:39-41",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 9:39-41",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Then Peter arose and went with them ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Doubtless God inclined him so to do, intending to work an extraordinary miracle by him, for the manifestation of his truth and glory. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And when he was come ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— To Tabitha’s house; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "they brought him into the upper chamber ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Where she was laid out. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And all the widows ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Who had been relieved by her benevolence; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "stood by him weeping, showing the coats, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — Here was no need of mourning women to be hired: the death of this woman was a common loss; these coats were made by her in her life-time, to clothe the poor and naked therewith. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "But Peter put them all forth ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— That he might with the more freedom pour out his soul before God in prayer on this occasion, and not be disturbed with their mournful lamentations. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "kneeled down and prayed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— In his healing Eneas there was an implicit prayer; but in this greater work he addressed himself to God in solemn prayer, as Christ did when he raised Lazarus; but Christ’s prayer was with the authority of a Son, who quickens whom he will; Peter’s with the submission of a servant, who is under direction, and therefore he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "kneeled down ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "when he offered it. And then rising, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and turning to the body, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "said",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — As with the voice of authority, in the name and presence of his great Lord, the Sovereign of life and death; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Tabitha, arise ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Words which were immediately accompanied with a divine power, so that she ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "opened her eyes, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and seeing ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Peter, sat up ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Showing that she was really and truly alive. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And when he had called the saints and widows — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Who were all in sorrow for her death, and were near the chamber, waiting impatiently for the event; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he presented her alive ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— And in perfect health, as all were that were miraculously cured. Who can imagine the surprise of Dorcas, when called back to life? or of her friends, when they saw her alive? For the sake of themselves, and the poor, there was cause of rejoicing; and much more for such a confirmation of the gospel. Yet to herself it was matter of resignation, not joy, to be called back to these scenes of vanity: but, doubtless, her remaining days were still more zealously spent in the service of her Saviour and her God. Thus was a richer treasure laid up for her in heaven, and she afterward returned to a more exceeding weight of glory, than that from which so astonishing a providence had recalled her for a season.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "9:36-43 Many are full of good words, who are empty and barren in good works; but Tabitha was a great doer, no great talker. Christians who have not property to give in charity, may yet be able to do acts of charity, working with their hands, or walking with their feet, for the good of others. Those are certainly best praised whose own works praise them, whether the words of others do so or not. But such are ungrateful indeed, who have kindness shown them, and will not acknowledge it, by showing the kindness that is done them. While we live upon the fulness of Christ for our whole salvation, we should desire to be full of good works, for the honour of his name, and for the benefit of his saints. Such characters as Dorcas are useful where they dwell, as showing the excellency of the word of truth by their lives. How mean then the cares of the numerous females who seek no distinction but outward decoration, and who waste their lives in the trifling pursuits of dress and vanity! Power went along with the word, and Dorcas came to life. Thus in the raising of dead souls to spiritual life, the first sign of life is the opening of the eyes of the mind. Here we see that the Lord can make up every loss; that he overrules every event for the good of those who trust in him, and for the glory of his name.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
